From: djb@silverton.berkeley.edu (D. J. Bernstein)
Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
Subject: Re: Creeping featuritis (post --rant --flame)
Date: 2 Dec 93 20:51:43 GMT

In article <MIB.93Dec2073948@geech.gnu.ai.mit.edu> mib@geech.gnu.ai.mit.edu (Michael I Bushnell) writes:
> I don't understand.

Okay. I'll explain slowly.

1. There is no need to extend the tar format to handle split files. The
splitting information can be carried in filenames, _as if_ the user had
physically replaced a big file FOO with a directory FOO containing lots
of little files FOO/0, FOO/32768, etc.; here FOO/n means ``FOO starting
at byte n.''

2. The same FOO/n format happens to handle sparse files as well. Bonus!

3. My understanding is that GNU tar uses incompatible format extensions
to handle split files and sparse files. That's pointless. It means that
somebody failed to _think_ before implementing the features.

4. GNU tar also has literally hundreds of lines of code to handle split
files and sparse files. The vast bulk of this complexity is unnecessary
and could be replaced by a much simpler, shorter set of mechanisms.

5. Finally---to get back to Brandon's point---the split file and sparse
file handling doesn't belong in the tar program per se. It would not be
difficult to write a separate program which handled those functions and
hooked nicely into GNU tar. One advantage is that you would not have to
repeat all the same handling in cpio. Another advantage---probably even
more important---is orthogonality. Only one program would pay attention
to sparse files, for example, so you'd only have to change that program
if you wanted to take advantage of some system feature to handle sparse
files more efficiently. Or the user could even substitute his own tool:
maybe he wants to handle sparse files, split files, _and_ tjkyrq files,
whatever those are.

---Dan

------------------------------

From: djb@silverton.berkeley.edu (D. J. Bernstein)
Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
Subject: Re: Creeping featuritis (post --rant --flame)
Date: 2 Dec 93 21:03:40 GMT

In article <2dknld$hs1@ftp.derwent.co.uk> tim@derwent.co.uk (Tim Morley x222) writes:
> In article <1993Dec210.51.14.7664@silverton.berkeley.edu> djb@silverton.berkeley.edu (D. J. Bernstein) writes:
> > Yeah, brilliant. What happens when thirty different programs like this
> > are running on the system? Boom, three megabytes gone---provided you
> > can fit each of your monster applications into a mere 100K.
> Never heard of links???

I said _different_ programs.

Oops, no, now I see the light. There _are_ no different programs. This 
one monster application puts together the compression and archiving and
splitting features _so well_ that _no other programmer_ will _ever_ want
to put the same features into a _new_ program.

Is that what you're saying?

Back to reality. There is, believe it or not, more than one monster
application in the world. For the same reason that _you_ throw _your_
set of small functions into _your_ big program, _other_ people throw 
_their_ sets of small functions into _their_ big programs. The result,
as I said, is thirty different programs, each eating a hefty chunk of
memory.

---Dan

