From: tzs@stein2.u.washington.edu (Tim Smith)
Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
Subject: Re: Creeping featuritis (post --rant --flame)
Date: 3 Dec 1993 00:20:58 GMT

Michael I Bushnell <mib@geech.gnu.ai.mit.edu> wrote:
>   The reason that multi-volume support may need to be in tar is so that
>   a file can be bigger than a volume.  If each file are smaller than a volume,
>   then you can make each volume a complete archive by simply using tar
>   multiple times.  A script/program could partition the files that are
>   to be archived into sets that would fit on single volumes, and then
>   invoke tar for each set.
>
>Incorrect.  Such files are probably very large, which means that the
>filesystems they are on cannot be assumed to hold both them and the
>split versions.  As a result, you cannot use such a scheme for file

What split versions?  If all files are smaller than the space on an
archive volume, you do not have to split any files.  You take a list
of all files to be archived and their sizes, and solve a knapsack
problem.  Tar is then invoked multiple times, each invocation being
given the names of the files that have been assigned to the particular
archive volume being created.

It may be more efficient to deal with it all in tar.  I am not disputing
that.  The nit I was picking was with the assertion that you need to change
tar so as to make each volume be a complete archive.  Since that can be
achieved without changing tar unless there are individual files that are
too large for a volume, it seems more correct to me to say that it is the
support of large files that requires the changes to tar.

--Tim Smith

