From: pcg@aber.ac.uk (Piercarlo Grandi)
Subject: Re: THE ULTIMATE FAQ ANSWER
Reply-To: pcg@aber.ac.uk (Piercarlo Grandi)
Date: Fri, 3 Dec 1993 00:16:51 GMT

>>> On 2 Dec 93 01:53:17, marca@ncsa.uiuc.edu (Marc Andreessen) said:

Marc> In article <2ddhv8$d0e@paperboy.osf.org> crow@osf.org (Darrell Crow) writes:
 
Darrell>  2) The Software Developer statically binds in the Motif "Runtime Copy" (as 
Darrell>     defined in the license supplement).  Applications are shipped with Motif 
Darrell>     "Runtime Copies".

Darrell>    There are three variants: [...]

Darrell>    B. Developer is a Full Distribution Rights Licensee of OSF/Motif or has a 
Darrell>       University Site License.  

Darrell>       License Reqs.:     The application distributed by the licensee 
Darrell>                          (developer) may be installed on any system, 
Darrell>                          whether or not the system already has a Motif 
Darrell>                          license.  
Darrell>       Royalty Reqs.:     No royalties will be due OSF in this instance.

Marc> Guess what?  Everyone who implied otherwise over the last couple of
Marc> weeks has been DEAD WRONG.  Congratulations, all.

The only congratulations go to OSF for having introduced runtime
royalties in most/many cases, and in such a complicated fashion that
in order to know whether your copy of a binary is legitimate without
paying royalties one needs to:

  1) obtain and understand a rather complicated set of license
     conditions

  2) determine whether the copy is statically or dynamically
     linked, and with which libraries.

  3) find out which library version was used in the copy.

  4) ask the developer of the copy which license *they* have got.

To me it is this that looks DEAD WRONG.

It's not suprising that several people were confused.

What about the OSF reverting to the way simpler and more common 1.1.x
conditions (no runtime royalties if statically linked, period)?

What about using libraries for which the problem simply does not arise?

